A simple and robust test object for the assessment of isotropic diffusion 
kurtosis.

Phillips J(1), Charles-Edwards GD.

Author information:
(1)Institute of Life Science, College of Medicine, Swansea University, Singleton 
Park, Swansea, UK; Medical Engineering and Physics, King's College London, 
Faraday Building, 124-126, Denmark Hill, London, UK; Medical Physics, St. 
Thomas' Hospital, Westminster Bridge Road, London, UK.

PURPOSE: To create a robust test object for the assessment of isotropic 
diffusion kurtosis and to investigate the relationships between barrier 
concentration and kurtosis and diffusion coefficients.
THEORY AND METHODS: Diffusion kurtosis imaging is an extension of conventional 
diffusion-weighted magnetic resonance imaging which provides a means of 
assessing the degree to which diffusion processes of spin-bearing particles are 
non-Gaussian, a property that is quantified by the kurtosis. We present a set of 
test objects, each possessing a different concentration of colloidal dispersion, 
allowing barrier concentration of the dispersed colloidal particles to be 
related to the kurtosis of the water diffusion. Diffusion coefficients from the 
kurtosis model and the monoexponential model are compared.
RESULTS: A relationship between barrier concentration and kurtosis is found, 
demonstrating that the diffusion process becomes less Gaussian as the barrier 
concentration is increased. Differences in the two estimates for the diffusion 
coefficients are examined. The test object is robust, displaying long-term 
reproducibility of results.
CONCLUSIONS: Colloidal dispersions provide a suitable and stable test object for 
the assessment and reproducibility measurements of kurtosis.

